da. &#10;Annual registration &amp; home visits hardly sounds excessively draconian (although it does depend on the terms and application of the 'right to enter the home' thing - it shouldn't be a guilty till proven innocent thing). &#10;It's not exactly saying:&#10;&quot;that if you send your child to a school, you are less likely to be a child abuser.&quot;&#10;rather that if you send your child to a school it's more likely someone will spot that they are being abused. &#10;--&#10;Wow. I'm almost defending government policy. Yikes. Better move to another thread where I can rant about something.. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="873" language="en" documentId="893" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="BrokenFace" date="06 November 2009 3:18pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6744300" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="893" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="311"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="312" end="531"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="532" end="556"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="557" end="641"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="642" end="752"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="753" end="755"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="756" end="873"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63"/></xmi:XMI>